description.p:
Tomoxetine, (R)-(-)-N-methyl-3-(2-methylphenoxy)-3-phenylpropylamine, is usually administered as the hydrochloride salt.


Tomoxetine was first disclosed in U.S. Pat. No. 4,314,081. The word "tomoxetine" will be used here to refer to any acid addition salt or the free base of the molecule.


See, for example, Gehlert, et al., Neuroscience Letters, 157, 203-206 (1993), for a discussion of tomoxeline's activity as a norepinophrine reuptake inhibitor;

Duloxetine, N-methyl-3-(1-naphthalenyloxy)-3-(2-thienyl)propanamine, is usually administered as the hydrochloride salt and as the (+) enantiomer.


It was first taught by U.S. Pat. No. 4,956,388, which shows its high potency.


The word "duloxetine" will be used here to refer to any acid addition salt or the free base of the molecule;
